{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"83c3329b-dc9e-4e92-9c97-8b816d9962bf","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run`** builds and launches the project automatically.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport). Avoid writing logs/debug output to stdout — use stderr instead.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot Chat panel in agent mode and your server's tools should appear automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4fd722a-203c-4732-b3cf-617787ff58c2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The file doesn't exist or is empty. That's fine — the user said they built it, so I can give them the configuration guidance based on standard .NET MCP server setup.","outputTokens":261},"id":"f1b24cd4-c627-4213-b318-ee23de6058be","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:53.090Z","parentId":"9f3a90b3-72e7-4203-9a1b-0f66a6227b77"}
